  "prompt": "Are there specific laws targeting money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations. In the United States, key laws include the Bank Secrecy Act and the USA PATRIOT Act, which require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and implement compliance programs. Internationally, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering. These laws typically require:\n\n1. Customer due diligence\n2. Transaction monitoring\n3. Reporting of suspicious activities\n4. Record-keeping requirements\n5. Penalties for non-compliance\n\nThe specific details and enforcement can vary by jurisdiction.",
